# **How to use this brief**

This document is the complete instruction set Claude needs to build landing pages for Image Foundry. It does not need supplementary input — everything required is contained here.

The brief is structured as follows:

- Section 2 — Who Image Foundry is: brand identity, tone of voice, and what makes the studio distinctive

- Section 3 — The audiences: what each target group cares about and how to speak to them

- Section 4 — What the research shows: the structural and copy principles that drive conversion for creative agencies

- Section 5 — Landing page structure: the exact page architecture Claude should follow

- Section 6 — Copy guidance: headlines, CTAs, tone rules, and what to avoid

- Section 7 — Brand rules: colours, typography, and visual direction Claude should apply

- Section 8 — Page specifications: separate guidance for the property and product pages

Claude should read all sections before producing any output. The brand voice in Section 2 and the structural rules in Section 4 are equally important as the specific copy guidance in Section 6.

# **Who Image Foundry is**

## **The company in plain terms**

Love Image Foundry is a Manchester-based CGI and product visualisation studio with over 20 years of experience. The studio produces high-end computer-generated imagery (CGI), animation, and interactive visual content for two primary client types: property developers and their marketing teams, and product manufacturers in sectors such as kitchen, bedroom, bathroom, and consumer goods.

Image Foundry does not describe itself as a production house. It positions itself as a strategic partner — one that understands the end customer deeply enough to guide clients toward CGI that performs better in the market, not just looks better on screen.

The studio has offices in Manchester, London, and New Delhi. It has produced CGI content for Channel 4, ITV, BBC, Discovery Channel and National Geographic, including work on BAFTA and Emmy award-winning productions.

## **The tagline and value proposition**

| **Tagline** Persuasive CGI |
| --- |

| **Value proposition** By understanding your customers' behaviour, we help you market products and properties more effectively. With our persuasive CGI, you can reach more customers more often and get a higher return on your marketing spend. |
| --- |

## **The four messaging pillars**

All Image Foundry copy should flow from one or more of these four pillars:

| **Pillar 1** | Deep customer understanding — how your customer thinks and behaves is the key to everything we do. We develop CGI tailored to your audience's needs and aspirations. |
| --- | --- |
| **Pillar 2** | Strategic guidance — we partner with our clients to go beyond content creation and provide strategic direction. From content type to channel, we guide you to a compelling collection of content. |
| **Pillar 3** | Better outcomes — our unique approach to CGI gets better results. Our CGI collections capture the imagination and inspire action, turning interest into leads. |
| **Pillar 4** | People first — people are our first consideration for all aspects of our business: team culture, client relationships and customer-centric CGI. |

## **The four tone attributes**

Every piece of copy Claude writes for Image Foundry must reflect these four qualities simultaneously:

| **Conversational** | Approachable, genuine, informal but not flippant. We write how we talk. Plain language. No hiding behind jargon or pompous words. Direct and easy to understand. |
| --- | --- |
| **Considered** | Deliberate, decisive, authoritative, empathetic. We think first, formulate a considered position, and state it decisively. Not ambiguous. Simple, direct, active language. |
| **Practical** | Tangible, specific, direct, action-focused. Crystal clear about what we do and what it means for the client. 'You' not 'we'. Emphasise tangible benefits. |
| **Empowering** | Enabling, motivational, encouraging. We embolden clients and equip them with the tools to get better outcomes. Optimism and conviction in every word. |

## **Tone in practice — like this, not like this**

| **✓  Like this** Show your customers what it's like to live in your property — on a sunny spring morning, a cosy winter evening or getting home from work. For your next campaign, use compelling CGI that helps you reach more of your customers in more places, so when they're ready to make a decision, you're top of mind. Getting started is simple. Tell us what you're marketing. We'll work to understand your customers and together identify a collection of CGI assets that will go much further. | **✗  Not like this** We are constantly pushing ourselves to create and refine CGI images to an ever greater standard, with a creative process that is as unforgiving as it is insightful. We combine artistry and professionalism with constantly evolving VR animation technology, allowing audiences to explore your vision from every angle. Contact us today to discuss your project. |
| --- | --- |

## **Language rules — words to use and avoid**

| **Use these words** | **Avoid these words** |
| --- | --- |
| CGI, visual content, visuals, CGI asset pack, CGI marketing assets, CGI collection, life moment shots, makes people take action, culturally diverse | Visualisations, emotive, engage, immerse, experience, CGI technical jargon, inspire your audience, we design CGI, architects, interior designers, your audience, top tips, check out |

→ *Always use UK English: -ise/-isation endings. No exclamation marks. Use contractions (we**'**re, you**'**ll, it**'**s). Address clients as **'**you**'**, not **'**our clients**'**.*

→ *CTA language that sounds like us: **'**Chat to us**'**, **'**Tell us about your project**'**, **'**Let**'**s talk**'**, **'**Tell me more**'**, **'**Talk to the team**'**. NOT: **'**Contact us**'**, **'**Subscribe**'**, **'**Sign up**'**.*

# **The audiences**

Image Foundry serves two distinct audiences. Each gets its own landing page. The pages share the same visual identity and tone but use different hero imagery, headlines, and body copy tailored to what each audience cares about most.

## **Audience A — Property developers and their marketing teams**

| **Who they are** | Property developers, development managers, marketing directors and marketing managers working on residential and commercial developments — typically selling off-plan (before construction is complete). |
| --- | --- |
| **Their core problem** | They need to sell properties — sometimes entire phases — before a brick has been laid. They need buyers to feel emotionally connected to a home that does not yet exist. |
| **What they fear** | Slow off-plan sales, buyers who can't visualise the finished product, marketing imagery that looks generic or low quality, missing launch deadlines, spending on imagery that doesn't convert. |
| **What they want** | CGI that sells. Imagery that makes buyers stop and feel something. A studio that understands the property market, not just pixels. Fast turnaround. One team they can trust. |
| **Value proposition** | Our CGI helps property developers sell more, faster. Because we understand what makes buyers commit — not just what makes images look impressive. |

## **Audience B — Product manufacturers (KBB and consumer goods)**

| **Who they are** | Marketing managers, brand managers and product directors at kitchen, bedroom, bathroom (KBB) manufacturers and broader consumer goods companies. They produce visual content for retail, e-commerce, brochures, and digital advertising. |
| --- | --- |
| **Their core problem** | Product photography is expensive, slow, and inflexible — especially when launching multiple colourways, configurations, or variants. CGI offers a faster, more scalable alternative that they may not yet fully understand or trust. |
| **What they fear** | CGI that looks fake. Investing in imagery that doesn't reflect the quality of the product. Long turnaround. Having to brief and manage a studio that doesn't understand their product category. |
| **What they want** | Imagery that is indistinguishable from photography. A studio that understands product marketing, not just rendering. Speed, flexibility, value, and a team that gets their brand. |
| **Value proposition** | Our product CGI is built on an understanding of your customers — what they respond to, what builds desire, and what makes them buy. Better results from your marketing spend. |

# **What the research shows**

The following principles are drawn from a detailed review of the world's best creative agency landing pages — including Ragged Edge, Koto, Stink Studios, Dawn Creative, Instrument, Further, Made Thought, and Human Agency — and from sector-specific research into CGI and visualisation studios. These are the structural and copy patterns that drive conversion for premium service-based businesses.

## **The four structural rules**

| **Rule 1: The work IS the above-the-fold visual** Without exception, the best agency pages use a real piece of client work as the primary visual — not a stock image, not an abstract graphic. For Image Foundry, this means the hero section should be dominated by a full-bleed, best-in-class CGI from the portfolio. The image does the selling before a single word is read. |
| --- |

| **Rule 2: Frame portfolio work as solved problems, not produced assets** The most effective pages describe work using this formula: [Client] faced [specific commercial challenge]. [Studio] created [brief description] to solve it. [Specific, measurable outcome]. Example: 'This Manchester developer needed marketing imagery before planning was confirmed. We produced a full suite of exterior and interior CGIs within 14 working days. 85% of Phase 1 sold off-plan within 6 weeks.' This structure transforms a portfolio showcase into a business case. |
| --- |

| **Rule 3: Social proof hierarchy — what actually persuades B2B buyers** 1st — Specific commercial outcome metrics ('85% of units sold off-plan within 6 weeks') 2nd — Named testimonials with job title and company ('Sarah Jones, Marketing Director, Redrow') 3rd — Recognisable client names (logos or listed names) 4th — Press or awards mentions 5th — Generic star ratings or 'trusted by X clients' — the weakest form. Avoid for a premium service. |
| --- |

| **Rule 4: CTA language for landing pages receiving paid traffic** Relational CTAs ('Let's talk', 'Tell us about your project') suit reputation-led warm inbound. Transactional CTAs ('Request a free CGI sample', 'Book a discovery call') suit cold paid traffic — more measurable, clear value exchange. For Image Foundry Google Ads pages: use a transactional CTA as the primary action. Include a softer relational secondary option. |
| --- |

## **The headline patterns that work**

Across the best agency pages reviewed, effective headlines follow one of three structures:

| **Pattern** | **Real example** | **For Image Foundry** |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Transformation frame — before/after promise | *"**Your brand is a sleeping giant. Let**'**s wake it up.**"** — Dawn Creative* | Property: "Your development deserves imagery that sells it before it's built." Product: "Your product deserves better than a photoshoot." |
| Identity + differentiator — who you are, then what makes you different | *"**We**'**re a global creative studio. From the thinking to the making, it all happens in-house.**"** — Stink Studios* | "We're a CGI studio. From your drawings and specifications to finished marketing imagery — all produced in-house, to deadline." |
| Provocation — a mild opinion that filters clients | *"**We make ambitious ideas for ambitious brands.**"** — Koto* | Property: "The developers who trust us to sell it before it exists." Product: "For brands who want their product to stop people scrolling." |

# **Landing page structure — section by section**

The following is the required section order for both landing pages. Each section includes what it must contain, the design intent, and specific guidance for Claude.

## **Section 1 — Hero (above the fold)**

| **Purpose** | Stop the visitor. Establish that this is a premium studio. Communicate the core offer in under 5 seconds. |
| --- | --- |
| **Visual** | Full-bleed, best-in-class CGI image from the Image Foundry portfolio relevant to the target audience. Full viewport height. Image is the hero. |
| **Headline** | Large, bold, Barlow Condensed caps. 5–8 words maximum. Uses one of the three headline patterns above. Overlaid on the image with sufficient contrast. |
| **Subheadline** | 1–2 sentences maximum. Plain body text. Supports and expands the headline. Must communicate outcome or differentiator. |
| **CTA** | Single primary CTA button. For paid traffic: transactional ('Book a discovery call' or 'Tell us about your project'). Prominent, high contrast. |
| **Nav** | Minimal. Logo only or logo plus one anchor link. No full website navigation — this leaks paid traffic. |

## **Section 2 — Value proposition strip**

| **Purpose** | Quickly establish why Image Foundry is different from any other CGI studio. |
| --- | --- |
| **Format** | Short, punchy. 2–3 sentences or a 3-column icon strip. Not a paragraph block. |
| **Content** | Pull from the core value proposition: understanding your customers' behaviour → more effective marketing → better return on spend. The 'Persuasive CGI' positioning. |

## **Section 3 — Portfolio showcase (3 curated examples)**

| **Purpose** | Do the selling visually. Show the quality of work. Then frame it as a solved business problem. |
| --- | --- |
| **Format** | 3 case study tiles. Each tile: large image + project description using the Ragged Edge formula. |
| **Copy formula** | [Client or development name] needed [specific challenge]. We produced [brief description]. [Outcome — if available, include a metric]. |
| **Examples** | Property: 'A Manchester developer needed to launch a 200-unit scheme before construction began. We delivered a full suite of exterior and interior CGI within 14 working days.' Product: 'A KBB brand needed to launch 6 colourways simultaneously. We produced all imagery from a single 3D model — no photoshoots, consistent quality across the range.' |

## **Section 4 — Social proof**

| **Purpose** | Reduce risk. Build trust. Make the visitor feel they are in safe hands. |
| --- | --- |
| **Format** | 2 named testimonials with job title and company name. Plus a client logo row (if available). Testimonials are the priority — make space for them. |
| **Placeholder copy** | If real testimonials are not provided, Claude should write placeholder testimonials in brackets labelled [PLACEHOLDER — replace with real client quote] that demonstrate the format and tone expected. |
| **Tone** | Testimonials should describe the outcome and the experience of working with the team — not just say 'the work was great'. |

## **Section 5 — Process (how it works)**

| **Purpose** | Remove the 'how do I even start?' anxiety. Make taking the next step feel simple and low-risk. |
| --- | --- |
| **Format** | 3 numbered steps. Brief. Conversational. Action-focused. |
| **Example steps** | 1. Tell us what you're marketing — 'Drop us a line and tell us about your project.' 2. We get under the skin of your customers — 'We work to understand what your buyers respond to, so the CGI we produce is built to persuade them.' 3. You get CGI that works — 'From first brief to finished assets, we keep it simple, fast, and focused on results.' |

## **Section 6 — Final CTA**

| **Purpose** | Capture the visitor who has scrolled through the whole page but hasn't yet clicked. |
| --- | --- |
| **Format** | Full-width colour band (IF Pink or IF Blue). Bold headline CTA. 1–2 sentence support copy. CTA button. Phone number and email address visible. |
| **Headline** | Direct, warm, action-oriented. Not 'Contact us'. Try: 'Ready to sell with imagery that actually works?' or 'Tell us what you're building. We'll take it from there.' |
| **Contact** | Phone: 0161 302 1580. Email: hello@loveimagefoundry.com. Include both visibly. |

# **Copy guidance — specific and ready to use**

## **Headline options for the property page**

| **Property page — suggested headlines (Claude to select the strongest or write variations)** "SELL IT BEFORE IT'S BUILT" — Barlow Condensed caps. Direct. Outcome-led. "CGI THAT SELLS OFF-PLAN" — Simple, specific, unambiguous. "YOUR DEVELOPMENT. REAL BEFORE IT EXISTS." — Two short sentences. Transformation frame. "THE IMAGERY THAT MOVES PROPERTY" — Results-focused. Confident. "WHAT IF YOUR BUYERS COULD SEE IT BEFORE YOU BUILD IT?" — Question format. Creates curiosity. |
| --- |

## **Headline options for the product page**

| **Product page — suggested headlines (Claude to select the strongest or write variations)** "PERSUASIVE CGI. BUILT FOR YOUR PRODUCT." — Tagline-anchored. Direct. "YOUR PRODUCT. EVERY ANGLE. NO PHOTOSHOOT." — Problem-solution compressed into a headline. "CGI THAT SELLS MORE THAN A PHOTOGRAPH" — Provocation. Challenges the status quo. "PRODUCT IMAGERY THAT MAKES PEOPLE STOP SCROLLING" — Outcome-led. Digital-channel relevant. "THE VISUAL DIFFERENCE BETWEEN BROWSING AND BUYING" — Identifies the specific commercial moment. |
| --- |

## **Value proposition copy — property page**

Use one of these as the hero subheadline or value strip. Adapt to fit the visual context:

- Your buyers need to feel at home before the foundations are in. We make that happen — with CGI built on a deep understanding of what drives property decisions.

- We've spent 20 years working out what makes buyers say yes to a property they haven't stepped inside. Our CGI is the result.

- From off-plan apartments to full housing developments, we produce CGI that makes your marketing material as compelling as the finished homes will be.

## **Value proposition copy — product page**

Use one of these as the hero subheadline or value strip:

- Your customers make decisions based on how a product makes them feel. We make CGI that captures that feeling — at a fraction of the cost of a photoshoot.

- One 3D model. Every colourway, configuration, and angle. All the imagery you need to launch — produced faster and more consistently than photography.

- We don't just make your product look good. We make it look like something your customers have to have.

